bq-open

Browse BigQuery tables across one or more GCP projects via fzf and
open the selected table(s) in the GCP console. Press TAB to select
several tables and Enter to open and copy all of them at once.

Projects are read from the environment variable BQ_SEARCH_PATH, which
must be set before calling this function:

  export BQ_SEARCH_PATH=my-project-prod:my-project-dev

BQ_SEARCH_PATH is a colon-separated list of GCP project IDs. Tables
from all listed projects are merged into a single picker, with each
entry shown as "project:dataset.table".

SANDBOX SUPPORT
  Optionally, set SANDBOX_BQ_PROJECT to a GCP project ID to include
  tables from a sandbox project. Sandbox entries appear in purple in
  the picker, prefixed with "[sandbox]".

  Set SANDBOX_BQ_DATASETS to a colon-separated list of dataset IDs to
  fetch from that project:

    export SANDBOX_BQ_PROJECT=my-sandbox-project
    export SANDBOX_BQ_DATASETS=dataset_a:dataset_b

  Both variables must be set together; SANDBOX_BQ_PROJECT alone has no
  effect.

CACHING
  The table list is cached in ~/.cache/bq-open/ keyed by the set of
  projects and sandbox variables. On the first run the list is fetched
  from BigQuery; subsequent runs load instantly from the cache.

  The fzf header shows how old the cache is. To refresh it, select
  the "--- REFRESH CACHE ---" entry at the top of the list; this
  deletes the cache files and re-fetches all tables before re-opening
  the picker.

SELECTION
  TAB toggles multi-select; Enter confirms. For every selected table
  the function:
  1. Prints the kind and fully-qualified name ("TABLE:
     project.dataset.table") and the GCP console URL to stdout, one
     pair per line.
  2. Copies all selected tables to the clipboard as a single multi-
     format payload: rich text / HTML hyperlinks (one per line) for
     editors, mail and chat, plus Markdown links as the plain-text
     flavor (macOS uses a Swift NSPasteboard helper; falls back to
     plain Markdown via pbcopy, or xclip/xsel on Linux).
  3. Opens every selected URL in the system browser (open on macOS,
     xdg-open on Linux).

The fzf preview pane shows the full table schema via
"bq show --format=prettyjson".

Requires: bq (Google Cloud SDK), fzf, jq.
Environment: BQ_SEARCH_PATH (required unless SANDBOX_BQ_PROJECT is set),
             SANDBOX_BQ_PROJECT (optional), SANDBOX_BQ_DATASETS (optional).
